CHIBA-EP-138



 
Uncertainty of Velocity in -Minkowski Spacetime 




Ken-Ichi Tezuka(e-mail: tezuka@graduate.chiba-u.jp)   




Graduate School of Science and Technology, Chiba University, Japan 




 
A velocity of a point particle in the -Minkowski spacetime is investigated. 
Characteristic points of the spacetime are that the Poincare group becomes a 
quantum group with , which is a mass dimension parameter, and is a 
kind of non-commutative geometry. We consider a particle in a
coordinate space instead of it in a momentum space which is discussed in many articles. 
We see that the particle's velocity has an uncertainty which depends on a length of  
particle's propagation. 


Introduction 
In cosmic ray physics, the following problems are not solved yet; anomalous 
detection of extremely high 
energy cosmic rays above the GZK cutoff ( eV) 
, and TeV- rays from Mrk 501 and Mrk 421. It was 
suggested that the absence of 
the GZK cutoff is closely related to violation of the Lorentz invariance. If 
the Lorentz 
invariance is violated or deformed, there is the possibility to explain that there is not 
the GZK cutoff at  eV.
Therefore we have to consider a mechanism for the violation or deformation of the 
symmetry. 

One of 
the characteristic features with respect to quantum gravity is the Plack length. If 
we would like to deal with this as an observer independent scale, the special relativity 
becomes a deformed one which has two scales; a velocity  and a mass . This 
is called the doubly special relativity which 
is explicitly realized by the -Poincare algebra. 
The -Poincare algebra is defined by replacing the Poincare algebra with a 
quantum group (Hopf algebra) with a parameter .  
In the limit , the Hopf algebra is reduced to the ordinary Lie 
algebra. Majid and Ruegg have pointed out that the -deformed 
algebra is the symmetry in the -Minkowski spacetime in which
time and spatial coordinates are non-commutative.
Some authors have discussed particle's velocity formulae
 in the -Minkowski spacetime. In the 
arguments, 
it was assumed that a velocity is defined by  which is true 
in the commutative Minkowski spacetime. In, by applying the 
formula to a massless particle, it was  predicted that the speed of light is dependent 
on its energy  and the parameter .  
In, by changing the rule of differentiation with respect to 
momenta, it was mentioned that the speed of light is undeformed. However validity of using
the formula 
in the -Minkowski spacetime has not been discussed sufficiently yet. 
It is known that there exists some bases of the -Poincare algebra
, which are related 
with each other by redefinition of the translation operators 
. In other words, the -deformation of the Poincare 
algebra is not unique. Since the dispersion relation is given as the Casimir operator 
of the algebra, the 
particle's velocity depends which bases we use, if the formula 
 is used. In this paper we would like to consider a 
velocity by avoiding using the formula, and would like to compare results.
The present paper is organized as follows. In the next section, we review the 
-Minkowski 
spacetime and the -Poincare algebra. Some velocity formulae are given explicitly by 
using the bicrossproduct basis. In the section 3, we will see that the action of a free 
particle does not depend on , and  is interpreted as the expectation value of 
photon's velocity. There is the deviation of the photon's velocity from the value , 
because of the spacetime 
non-commutativity. The section 4 is devoted to the summary and the remarks.
Review of -Minkowski spacetime 
In this section, we briefly review the -deformed Poincare algebra, and present 
discussions about velocities of particles in the -Minkowski spacetime.

Drinfeld and Jimbo have proposed a 
prescription how to define a quantum 
enveloping algebra, which is q-deformation of an universal enveloping algebra of a simple 
Lie algebra, in terms of a Hopf algebra.  Since the
Poincare algebra is not a simple Lie algebra, it is not straightforward to apply  
the Drinfeld-Jimbo prescription to the Poincare algebra. It is well known that the 
Poincare algebra can be obtained by contraction of the  dimensional AdS algebra 
 which is a simple Lie algebra. In the 
limit  which is the AdS radius, the AdS algebra is reduced to the Poincare 
algebra. The contraction  with 
 of the q-deformed AdS algebra gives a -deformed Poincare 
algebra
. Here  is a real constant, and  is an imaginary 
parameter(It is possible to use a real parameter 
