It was noticed that quantum groups can be realized as 
symmetries in non-commutative spaces(As a review article, see.)  
. The -Poincare algebra is the symmetry 
in the -Minkowski spacetime which is non-commutative;
[X^i,X^0]=1  X^i, 1 [X^i,X^j]=0. Although there are some bases of the algebra 
, 
all of them correspond to the commutator.
In the commutative Minkowski spacetime, a  particle's velocity  is written as 
v_i= E  p^i    with . Many authors have assumed that this 
relation is true also in the -Minkowski spacetime. For a 
massless particle, by solving () and using the formula () we have 
v^2=c^2 (2E  ).
So the velocity of a massless particle is deformed from the constant c, and has energy 
dependence. Because of the effect, the  has the constraint m from 
the astronomical observation of  rays. On 
the other hand, in, it was mentioned that the
rule for the differentiation with the momentum is changed since the momentum sum rule is 
-deformed. From the coproduct (), we notice that the sum of momenta 
 and  of two particles is deformed as
p_1+(-E_1  ) p_2
